data.content:
Here's the mapping from the framework reference:

| NUnit | xUnit equivalent |
|-------|-----------------|
| `[SetUp]` | **Constructor** |
| `[TearDown]` | **`IDisposable.Dispose`** |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]` | **`IClassFixture<T>`** with fixture's `Dispose` |

Converted code:

```csharp
// Shared fixture replaces [OneTimeSetUp] / [OneTimeTearDown]
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor replaces [SetUp]
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // IDisposable.Dispose replaces [TearDown]
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key points:
- **Per-test** setup/teardown → constructor + `IDisposable` (xUnit creates a new instance per test automatically)
- **One-time** setup/teardown → extract into a fixture class implementing `IDisposable`, then reference it via `IClassFixture<T>`
- The fixture is injected via the constructor — accept it as a parameter even if unused (`_`)
- If your setup/teardown is `async`, implement `IAsyncLifetime` (with `InitializeAsync`/`DisposeAsync`) instead
